.SS CONFIGURATION
\f[B]rinetd\-uv\f[R] supports two configuration formats:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Legacy format\f[R] (\f[CR].conf\f[R]) \- the original
space\-delimited format, compatible with the original rinetd.
Simple and easy to use for basic forwarding rules.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]YAML format\f[R] (\f[CR].yaml\f[R] / \f[CR].yml\f[R], version
2.1.0+) \- a structured format that adds support for load balancing with
multiple backends, health checking, weighted distribution, and client
affinity.
.PP
The format is detected automatically by file extension.
Both formats support the same core features (forwarding rules, access
control, global options).
Load balancing is available only in YAML format, while the
\f[CR]include\f[R] directive is available only in the legacy format.
.PP
A Python conversion script is provided to migrate legacy configurations
to YAML:
.IP
.EX
python3 tools/conf2yaml.py /etc/rinetd\-uv.conf > /etc/rinetd\-uv.yaml
.EE
.SS Forwarding Rules
Forwarding rules define how \f[B]rinetd\-uv\f[R] redirects connections
from one address/port to another.
Each rule specifies a listening (bind) address and a destination
(connect) address.
.PP
Both IP addresses and hostnames are accepted, including IPv6.
Service names (as defined in \f[CR]/etc/services\f[R]) can be used
instead of port numbers.
.SS Legacy Format
.IP
.EX
bindaddress bindport connectaddress connectport [options...]
.EE
.PP
For example:
.IP
.EX
206.125.69.81 80  10.1.1.2 80
.EE
.PP
Would redirect all connections to port 80 of the \[lq]real\[rq] IP
address 206.125.69.81, which could be a virtual interface, through
\f[B]rinetd\-uv\f[R] to port 80 of the address 10.1.1.2, which would
typically be a machine on the inside of a firewall which has no direct
routing to the outside world.
.PP
Although responding on individual interfaces rather than on all
interfaces is one of \f[B]rinetd\-uv\f[R]\[cq]s primary features,
sometimes it is preferable to respond on all IP addresses that belong to
the server.
In this situation, the special IP address \f[CR]0.0.0.0\f[R] can be
used:
.IP
.EX
0.0.0.0 23  10.1.1.2 23
.EE
.SS YAML Format
In YAML, each forwarding rule is an entry in the \f[CR]rules\f[R] list
with a unique \f[CR]name\f[R], a \f[CR]bind\f[R] address, and a
\f[CR]connect\f[R] destination:
.IP
.EX
rules\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] web\-forward
    bind\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]0.0.0.0:80/tcp\[dq]
    connect\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]10.1.1.2:80\[dq]
.EE
.PP
The \f[CR]bind\f[R] field can be a single address or a list (for fan\-in
from multiple listeners):
.IP
.EX
rules\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] web\-multi
    bind\f[B]:\f[R]
      \f[B]\-\f[R] \[dq]0.0.0.0:80/tcp\[dq]
      \f[B]\-\f[R] \[dq]0.0.0.0:443/tcp\[dq]
      \f[B]\-\f[R] \[dq][::]:80/tcp\[dq]
    connect\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]10.1.1.2:80\[dq]
.EE
.PP
The \f[CR]connect\f[R] field can be a single destination string or a
list of backends (for load balancing):
.IP
.EX
rules\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] web\-cluster
    connect\f[B]:\f[R]
      \f[B]\-\f[R] dest\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]web1.example.com:8080\[dq]
        weight\f[B]:\f[R] 2
      \f[B]\-\f[R] dest\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]web2.example.com:8080\[dq]
        weight\f[B]:\f[R] 1
.EE
.PP
See the \f[B]Load Balancing\f[R] section for details on multi\-backend
configuration.
.SS Protocol Specification
Ports default to TCP.
To specify the protocol, append \f[CR]/udp\f[R] or \f[CR]/tcp\f[R] to
the port number:
.PP
\f[B]Legacy format:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
206.125.69.81 80/tcp  10.1.1.2 8000/tcp
0.0.0.0 53/udp  8.8.8.8 53/udp
.EE
.PP
\f[B]YAML format:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
rules\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] dns\-forward
    bind\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]0.0.0.0:53/udp\[dq]
    connect\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]8.8.8.8:53/udp\[dq]
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] Mixed\-mode forwarding (TCP to UDP or UDP to TCP) is not
supported.
.SS Unix Domain Sockets
\f[B]rinetd\-uv\f[R] supports Unix domain sockets (also known as Unix
sockets or local sockets), allowing forwarding between TCP and Unix
sockets in any combination:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]TCP to Unix socket\f[R] \- Expose a Unix socket service over TCP
(e.g.\ Docker socket proxy)
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Unix socket to TCP\f[R] \- Accept connections on a Unix socket and
forward to TCP backend
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Unix to Unix\f[R] \- Forward between Unix sockets
.PP
Unix socket addresses use the \f[CR]unix:\f[R] prefix followed by the
socket path:
.IP
.EX
unix:/path/to/socket    # Filesystem socket (absolute path required)
unix:\[at]name              # Abstract namespace socket (Linux only)
.EE
.PP
No port number is required for Unix socket addresses.
.PP
\f[B]Legacy format examples:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
# TCP to Unix \- Docker socket proxy
0.0.0.0 2375/tcp unix:/var/run/docker.sock

# Unix to TCP forwarding with restricted permissions
unix:/var/run/myapp.sock 192.168.1.100 8080/tcp [mode=0660]

# Abstract namespace socket (Linux only)
0.0.0.0 9999/tcp unix:\[at]myservice
.EE
.PP
\f[B]YAML format examples:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
rules\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] docker\-proxy
    bind\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]0.0.0.0:2375/tcp\[dq]
    connect\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]unix:/var/run/docker.sock\[dq]

  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] unix\-to\-tcp
    bind\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]unix:/var/run/myapp.sock\[dq]
    connect\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]192.168.1.100:8080/tcp\[dq]
    mode\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]0660\[dq]
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Access control for Unix sockets:\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
For \f[B]filesystem sockets\f[R], access is controlled by filesystem
permissions on the socket file
.IP \[bu] 2
For \f[B]TCP endpoints\f[R], the standard allow and deny rules apply
.IP \[bu] 2
IP\-based access control does not apply to incoming Unix socket
connections (access rules in such case will be ignored)
.IP \[bu] 2
For \f[B]abstract sockets\f[R] (Linux), any process in the same network
namespace can connect
.PP
\f[B]Security considerations:\f[R]
.IP "1." 3
\f[B]Filesystem permissions\f[R]: By default, the socket file
permissions are determined by the process umask.
Use \f[CR][mode=0660]\f[R] (legacy) or \f[CR]mode: \[dq]0660\[dq]\f[R]
(YAML) to set explicit permissions.
.IP "2." 3
\f[B]Abstract sockets\f[R]: Accessible by any process in the same
network namespace \- use with caution.
The \f[CR]mode\f[R] option has no effect on abstract sockets.
.IP "3." 3
\f[B]Socket cleanup\f[R]: Filesystem sockets are automatically removed
on shutdown and before bind.
.PP
\f[B]Limitations:\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Maximum socket path length varies by system (Linux: 107, BSD: 103, some
other systems: 91)
.IP \[bu] 2
Unix sockets only support stream mode (SOCK_STREAM); datagram mode
(SOCK_DGRAM) or SCTP (SOCK_SEQPACKET) is not supported
.IP \[bu] 2
UDP forwarding cannot use Unix sockets
.IP \[bu] 2
Abstract namespace sockets are Linux\-specific and not portable
.IP \[bu] 2
Windows named pipes support is not tested although underlying libuv
declares they are covered, report a bug in case you need it.
.SS Per\-Rule Options
Per\-rule options modify the behavior of individual forwarding rules.
.PP
\f[B]Legacy format\f[R] uses square brackets after the rule:
\f[CR][option=value,option2=value2]\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]YAML format\f[R] uses rule\-level keys or per\-backend keys.
.SS UDP Timeout
Since UDP is a connectionless protocol, a timeout is necessary or
forwarding connections may accumulate with time and exhaust resources.
By default, if no data is sent or received on a UDP connection for 10
seconds, the other connection is closed.
.PP
\f[B]Legacy format:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
0.0.0.0 8000/udp  10.1.1.2 53/udp  [timeout=3600]
.EE
.PP
\f[B]YAML format:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
rules\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] dns\-forward
    bind\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]0.0.0.0:8000/udp\[dq]
    connect\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]10.1.1.2:53/udp\[dq]
    timeout\f[B]:\f[R] 3600
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] rinetd\-uv limits UDP connections to 5000 concurrent
outgoing connections per forwarding rule (configurable via
\f[CR]max\-udp\-connections\f[R]) to prevent file descriptor exhaustion.
When this limit is reached, the oldest (least recently used) connection
is automatically closed to make room for new connections.
.SS Source Address
A forwarding rule option allows binding to a specific local address when
sending data to the other end.
.PP
\f[B]Legacy format:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
192.168.1.1 80  10.1.1.127 80  [src=10.1.1.2]
.EE
.PP
\f[B]YAML format:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
rules\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] web\-forward
    bind\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]192.168.1.1:80/tcp\[dq]
    connect\f[B]:\f[R]
      \f[B]\-\f[R] dest\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]10.1.1.127:80\[dq]
        src\f[B]:\f[R] 10.1.1.2
.EE
.PP
Assuming the local host has two IP addresses, 10.1.1.1 and 10.1.1.2,
this rule ensures that forwarded packets are sent using source address
10.1.1.2.
.SS TCP Keepalive
TCP keepalive is enabled by default for all TCP connections to detect
dead connections.
To disable it for a specific forwarding rule:
.PP
\f[B]Legacy format:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
192.168.1.1 80/tcp  10.1.1.127 80/tcp  [keepalive=off]
.EE
.PP
\f[B]YAML format:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
rules\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] web\-forward
    bind\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]192.168.1.1:80/tcp\[dq]
    connect\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]10.1.1.127:80/tcp\[dq]
    keepalive\f[B]:\f[R] false
.EE
.PP
When enabled, keepalive probes are sent after 60 seconds of inactivity.
.SS DNS Refresh
For forwarding rules with backend hostnames (not IP addresses),
\f[B]rinetd\-uv\f[R] can automatically re\-resolve DNS hostnames at
configurable intervals.
This ensures that if a backend\[cq]s IP address changes, new connections
will use the updated address.
.PP
The global default is set via \f[CR]dns\-refresh\f[R] /
\f[CR]dns_refresh\f[R] (see \f[B]Global Options\f[R]).
Per\-rule overrides:
.PP
\f[B]Legacy format:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
0.0.0.0 8080/tcp backend.example.com 80 [dns\-refresh=300]
0.0.0.0 8081/tcp backend2.example.com 80 [dns\-refresh=0]
.EE
.PP
\f[B]YAML format:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
rules\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] web\-forward
    bind\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]0.0.0.0:8080/tcp\[dq]
    connect\f[B]:\f[R]
      \f[B]\-\f[R] dest\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]backend.example.com:80\[dq]
        dns_refresh\f[B]:\f[R] 300
.EE
.PP
Setting \f[CR]dns\-refresh=0\f[R] / \f[CR]dns_refresh: 0\f[R] disables
periodic DNS refresh for that rule/backend.
.PP
\f[B]Behavior:\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Hostname detection:\f[R] DNS refresh is only enabled for backend
(target) hostnames.
Rules with IP addresses (IPv4 or IPv6) automatically skip DNS refresh.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Existing connections:\f[R] Continue using the old IP address until
they close naturally.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]New connections:\f[R] Immediately use the newly resolved IP
address.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Failure\-triggered refresh:\f[R] After 3 consecutive connection
failures to a backend, DNS is re\-resolved immediately (regardless of
the timer interval).
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]SIGHUP compatibility:\f[R] Sending SIGHUP still forces immediate
re\-resolution of all hostnames (existing behavior preserved).
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Multiple IPs:\f[R] In case DNS returns multiple addresses for given
hostname \- the first one will be used; with random order in returned
set you may get frequent changes of IP assigned to given rule.
See also: \f[B]DNS Multi\-IP Automatic Load Balancing\f[R] in the
\f[B]Global Options\f[R] section.
.SS Unix Socket Mode
Set explicit file permissions for Unix domain socket files:
.PP
\f[B]Legacy format:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
unix:/var/run/restricted.sock 192.168.1.100 8080/tcp [mode=0660]
.EE
.PP
\f[B]YAML format:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
rules\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] restricted\-proxy
    bind\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]unix:/var/run/restricted.sock\[dq]
    connect\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]192.168.1.100:8080/tcp\[dq]
    mode\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]0660\[dq]
.EE
.SS Access Rules
Configuration files can contain allow and deny rules to control which
clients can connect.
Patterns can contain the characters: \f[CR]0\f[R]\-\f[CR]9\f[R],
\f[CR].\f[R] (period), \f[CR]?\f[R], and \f[CR]*\f[R].
The \f[CR]?\f[R] wildcard matches any one character.
The \f[CR]*\f[R] wildcard matches any number of characters, including
zero.
.PP
\f[B]Important:\f[R] Host names are \f[B]NOT\f[R] permitted in allow and
deny rules.
The performance cost of looking up IP addresses to find their
corresponding names is prohibitive.
Since \f[B]rinetd\-uv\f[R] is a single process server, all other
connections would be forced to pause during the address lookup.
.SS Legacy Format
In the legacy format, allow and deny rules can be \f[B]global\f[R] or
\f[B]per\-rule\f[R] depending on their position in the configuration
file.
.PP
\f[B]Global rules\f[R] appear before the first forwarding rule:
.IP
.EX
# Global access control (before any forwarding rules)
allow 192.168.2.*
deny 192.168.2.1?

# Forwarding rules follow
0.0.0.0 80/tcp 192.168.1.10 8080/tcp
.EE
.IP \[bu] 2
If at least one global allow rule exists, connections not matching any
global allow rule are rejected.
.IP \[bu] 2
If a connection matches any global deny rule, it is rejected.
.PP
\f[B]Per\-rule access control\f[R] appears after a specific forwarding
rule:
.IP
.EX
0.0.0.0 22 192.168.1.20 22
allow 10.0.0.*
deny 10.0.0.100
.EE
.IP \[bu] 2
Per\-rule allow/deny rules apply only to the preceding forwarding rule.
.IP \[bu] 2
The same logic applies: if allow rules exist for a rule, connections
must match at least one.
.SS YAML Format
In YAML, access control is configured per\-rule using the
\f[CR]access\f[R] block:
.IP
.EX
rules\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] web\-forward
    bind\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]0.0.0.0:80/tcp\[dq]
    connect\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]192.168.1.10:8080/tcp\[dq]
    access\f[B]:\f[R]
      allow\f[B]:\f[R]
        \f[B]\-\f[R] \[dq]192.168.*\[dq]
        \f[B]\-\f[R] \[dq]10.0.0.*\[dq]
      deny\f[B]:\f[R]
        \f[B]\-\f[R] \[dq]192.168.1.100\[dq]
        \f[B]\-\f[R] \[dq]*\[dq]
.EE
.PP
Rules are evaluated in order: allow rules checked first, then deny
rules.
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] Global access rules are not supported in YAML format \-
use per\-rule access control instead.
.SS Global Options
Global options configure server\-wide behavior.
All settings are optional and have sensible defaults.
.PP
